            ContentJson = """{"passingScore":80,"questionsPerQuiz":8,"shuffleOptions":true,"showExplanationsAfterSubmit":true,"questions":[{"id":"pl1","text":"What is the primary purpose of production lot tracking in Forge?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"To count how many parts are in inventory at any given time"},{"id":"b","text":"To trace batches of parts back to their origin for recall capability, quality investigations, and regulatory compliance","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"To schedule production runs on the shop floor"},{"id":"d","text":"To calculate the cost of goods sold for each part"}],"explanation":"Lot tracking provides full traceability from raw material receipt through production, inspection, and shipment. This is essential for recalls, FDA/medical compliance, supplier accountability, and quality investigations."},{"id":"pl2","text":"A lot record must always be linked to which of the following?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"A job and a production run"},{"id":"b","text":"A purchase order line and a supplier lot number"},{"id":"c","text":"A part — every lot must reference exactly one part","isCorrect":true},{"id":"d","text":"A QC inspection and a bin location"}],"explanation":"Part ID is the only required relationship. Every lot must be tied to exactly one part. Job, production run, purchase order line, and supplier lot number are all optional and depend on how the lot was created."},{"id":"pl3","text":"What format does Forge use for auto-generated lot numbers?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"BATCH-{partNumber}-{sequence}"},{"id":"b","text":"LOT-YYYYMMDD-NNN (e.g., LOT-20260415-001)","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"LR-{year}-{globalSequence}"},{"id":"d","text":"{partNumber}-{date}-{random}"}],"explanation":"Auto-generated lot numbers follow LOT-YYYYMMDD-NNN: a fixed 'LOT-' prefix, the UTC creation date, and a zero-padded daily sequence number. Custom lot numbers can be provided to override this format."},{"id":"pl4","text":"You receive raw material from a vendor. Which fields should you populate on the lot record?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Part ID, quantity, purchase order line ID, and supplier lot number","isCorrect":true},{"id":"b","text":"Part ID, quantity, job ID, and production run ID"},{"id":"c","text":"Part ID, quantity, and expiration date only"},{"id":"d","text":"Only lot number and quantity — the system fills in the rest"}],"explanation":"For vendor-received material, link the lot to the PO line (purchase order line ID) and record the supplier's own batch identifier (supplier lot number). Job and production run are for internally produced lots."},{"id":"pl5","text":"A customer reports a defect in parts they received. What is the first step in the recall workflow?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Shut down all production lines immediately"},{"id":"b","text":"Identify the lot number from the part's label, shipping record, or customer complaint, then trace that lot","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Contact the vendor and request a replacement shipment"},{"id":"d","text":"Delete the lot record to prevent further shipments"}],"explanation":"The first step is identifying the lot number and tracing that lot. Its history reveals the full chain: which jobs produced it, where remaining stock is stored, which QC inspections were performed, and which supplier material was used."},{"id":"pl6","text":"How does the lot detail panel present a lot's traceability?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Only the lot record fields and the associated part number"},{"id":"b","text":"A part header (part number, quantity, supplier lot, expiration) plus a single chronological Trace History timeline that merges jobs, production runs, purchase orders, bin locations, and QC inspections into one event stream","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Five separate tables — one each for jobs, production runs, purchase orders, bin locations, and inspections"},{"id":"d","text":"The financial cost breakdown of producing this lot"}],"explanation":"The detail panel shows a header (part number, quantity, supplier lot, expiration) and a Trace History timeline. Related records — jobs, production runs, purchase orders, bin locations, and QC inspections — are interleaved into one date-ordered event stream, each event with a type icon, reference number, description, and date. They are not displayed as five separate lists."},{"id":"pl7","text":"When should you set an expiration date on a lot record?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Always — every lot must have an expiration date for compliance"},{"id":"b","text":"When the material has a shelf life, such as adhesives, chemicals, or rubber compounds","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Only for lots received from vendors, never for internally produced lots"},{"id":"d","text":"Only when the customer specifically requests lot expiration tracking"}],"explanation":"Expiration dates are for materials with a shelf life — adhesives, chemicals, perishable components. The field is optional and should be null for non-perishable materials like metal stock or hardware."},{"id":"pl8","text":"Who can create lots and run traceability lookups?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Admins and Managers only"},{"id":"b","text":"Admins, Managers, Engineers, and Production Workers","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Admins, Managers, and Engineers — Production Workers can only view lots, not create them"},{"id":"d","text":"Everyone, including the Office Manager and the PM"}],"explanation":"Admins, Managers, Engineers, and Production Workers all get full access to lots. All four can create a lot and trace one. This matters on the floor: the operator who runs the batch or receives the material can record the lot themselves, without waiting on a supervisor."},{"id":"pl9","text":"What happens to a lot when it is deleted?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"It is wiped for good, so its traceability history is gone"},{"id":"b","text":"It disappears from the lists and lookups, but the record itself is kept for the audit trail and compliance","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Nothing — lots can never be removed once created"},{"id":"d","text":"It stays visible in the list but is marked with a strikethrough"}],"explanation":"Deleting a lot only hides it from the lists and traceability lookups — the record is never truly erased. Keeping the underlying data is deliberate: a regulated shop must be able to prove the full history of a lot even after it is retired, so the audit trail survives the delete."},{"id":"pl10","text":"On the Lots list you filter to a single part and see both lots you received from vendors and lots your shop produced. How do you tell which lots came from a vendor?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"The vendor-received lots are the ones linked to a purchase order and carrying the supplier's own lot number; in-house lots have neither and are tied to a job or production run instead","isCorrect":true},{"id":"b","text":"Vendor lots always have a red highlight in the list; in-house lots are shown in plain text"},{"id":"c","text":"There is no way to tell them apart on the list — you have to open each lot and read its notes"},{"id":"d","text":"Vendor lots always have an expiration date, so any lot without an expiration date was made in-house"}],"explanation":"A lot received from a vendor is linked to the purchase order line it arrived on and records the supplier's own lot number, so the detail panel shows a Supplier Lot row and a Purchase Order event on the trace timeline. A lot your shop produced is tied to a job (and production run) instead and has no supplier lot number. The expiration date is unrelated — it depends on whether the material has a shelf life, not on where the lot came from."}]}"""
