            ContentJson = """{"appRoute":"/lots","startButtonLabel":"Tour Production Lots","steps":[{"element":"app-page-header","popover":{"title":"The Lots List","description":"See every lot you have recorded in one table — its lot number, part, quantity, linked job, supplier lot, expiration, and the date it was created. Start here to create a new lot or look up the history of an existing one.","side":"bottom"}},{"element":".page-header app-input","popover":{"title":"Search Lots","description":"Find a lot fast. Search matches the lot number, the supplier's lot number, and the part number, so you can paste a number off a label, packing slip, or certificate and land on the right record. Type it, then press Enter or click Search.","side":"bottom"}},{"element":"[data-testid='new-lot-btn']","popover":{"title":"Create a New Lot","description":"Click New Lot to open the create form. Lots are always created by hand here. Pick the Part and enter a Quantity — both required; a linked job, supplier lot, expiration date, and notes are optional. The lot number is filled in for you when you save. If the part isn't set up yet, you can add it right in the form.","side":"bottom"}},{"element":".page-header","popover":{"title":"Quantity Can Be Fractional","description":"Open the create form and the Quantity field accepts fractional amounts, not just whole numbers. That lets you record material measured by weight, volume, or length exactly as it arrives — for example 12.5 kg or 3.75 m. Enter the real measured amount instead of rounding.","side":"bottom"}},{"element":"app-data-table","popover":{"title":"Open a Lot to Trace It","description":"Click any row to open that lot's detail panel. It opens over the list, and the view stays shareable and survives a refresh. This is how you go from 'which lot is this?' to its full history.","side":"left"}},{"element":"app-data-table","popover":{"title":"Reading the Trace Timeline","description":"Open a lot and its panel shows a header with the part, quantity, and — when set — the supplier lot and expiration. Below it, Trace History is one dated timeline: jobs, production runs, purchase orders, bin locations, and inspections are merged in order, each with an icon, a reference number, and a date. Read it top to bottom to follow the chain from receiving through production, inspection, and storage. A History tab records changes to the lot itself.","side":"left"}}]}"""
