            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 90,
            AppRoutes = """["/lots"]""",
            Tags = """["production-lots","reference","advanced"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Why Lots Are Create-and-Trace, Not Edit-in-Place\n\nThe Lots screen is built to **list**, **search**, **create**, and **trace** lots — and deliberately not to edit them field-by-field after the fact. A lot is a record of something that actually happened on the floor: this batch, this material, this quantity, received or produced on this day. In a regulated shop, quietly overwriting a lot's part or quantity a week later would break the very trust the lot record exists to provide.\n\nSo the working habit is: **get the lot right when you create it.** Pick the correct part, enter the real measured quantity, and record the supplier lot number off the packing slip while it is in front of you. If you catch a mistake right after creating a lot — say the quantity was fat-fingered — the cleanest fix is usually to create a corrected lot and note the correction, rather than treating the lot list like an editable spreadsheet. When a lot genuinely must be changed or removed after the fact, that is an administrator's call, made deliberately and with a reason, not an everyday click.\n\nThe lot's own History view records changes to the lot record, so any correction that does happen leaves a footprint.\n\n## What Deleting a Lot Really Means\n\nDeleting a lot does **not** erase it. The lot drops out of the list, out of search, and out of every traceability lookup — but the underlying record is kept. This is on purpose: months or years later, an auditor, a customer, or a recall investigation may still need to prove the full history of a lot that has long since been used up or retired. A shop that truly wiped the record could not answer that.\n\nBecause a deleted lot is hidden rather than destroyed, there is no self-service 'undo' button on the screen. If a lot was deleted by mistake and needs to come back into view, that recovery is an administrator's task, not something you redo from the Lots list. Treat deletion as a considered action, the same way you would treat voiding a paper traveler.\n\n## When the Lots Screen Is Turned Off, and Who Can Use It\n\nLot tracking is an **optional feature** an install can turn on or off. Not every shop needs formal lot traceability — a simple job shop making one-off parts may never enable it. When lot tracking is switched off for your site, the Lots screen simply is not there in the menu, and that is expected, not a bug. If your shop starts taking regulated or lot-controlled work and you need lots, ask an administrator to enable lot tracking.\n\nWhen the feature **is** on, four roles get full use of it: **Admins, Managers, Engineers, and Production Workers**. All four can create lots and trace them — there is no view-only tier. This is intentional: the operator receiving material or finishing a run is the right person to record the lot, so the floor is not blocked waiting on a supervisor. Office and project-management roles do not work in lots.\n\n## Sharing a Link to a Lot, and Picking Up an Unsaved One\n\n**Share the exact lot you are looking at.** When you open a lot's detail panel, the page keeps that lot in view even if you refresh, and the browser address for it points straight back to that same lot. So you can copy the address, paste it into a message to a colleague or into a quality record, and they land on the same lot's trace — not just the generic list. Other screens that mention a lot can link straight to it the same way.\n\n**Pick up where you left off.** If you start creating a new lot, get pulled away, and leave the form without saving, your typed-in values are not necessarily lost. When you come back to the Lots screen, it can reopen the New Lot form with what you had entered, so you finish the lot instead of starting over. This is handy on a busy floor where receiving gets interrupted mid-entry.\n\n## Scanning a Lot Label\n\nMany shops print lot numbers as barcodes on labels, travelers, and certificates. Scanning is faster and far less error-prone than typing a long lot number by hand. On this platform, scanning a lot label is handled on the **Quality** area: point the scanner at a lot barcode and it drops the value straight into the lot search there, taking you to that lot. The plain Lots list is for browsing and creating; when you have a physical label in hand and want to jump to its history, scan it from Quality. Either way, the goal is the same — get from a label to that lot's full trace without transcribing digits.\n\n## Why a Bin Can Go Missing From a Trace\n\nWhen you trace a lot, the **Bin Location** events tell you where units of that lot are physically stored. Those bin events are matched to the lot by two things together: the **part** and the **exact lot number** written on the bin's contents. Both have to agree for a bin to show up on the trace.\n\nThe practical gotcha: if someone tags a bin with a mistyped lot number — a transposed digit, an extra space, `LOT-20260415-001` versus `LOT-2026O415-001` — that bin will **not** appear in the lot's trace, even though the material is really sitting there. Nothing errors; the bin just silently goes missing from the history. So when you are running a recall and a lot's trace shows fewer bins than you expect, suspect a lot-number typo on the bin first. The fix is to correct the lot number on the bin contents so it matches the lot exactly. This is one more reason to scan lot labels instead of hand-keying them.","sections":[]}"""
